    "finalTextLength": 1342,
    "finalText": "Teams is still not something I’d call fully trustworthy for “today” reads.\n\nWhat I can confirm:\n- There’s a known gap in reliably retrieving recent Teams messages, and the system explicitly notes a need for a dedicated recent-message retrieval tool. [Source: ai_memory, 2026-05-19]\n- There was a Teams service restoration update saying messaging was functioning reliably again after a browser issue, with redundant monitoring and a 10-second monitoring protocol in place. But that message itself was from February 15, 2026, surfaced in a later record — so it tells us service was restored then, not that today’s retrieval layer is fully current. [Source: Teams DM summary, 2026-04-30, referencing message dated 2026-02-15]\n\nBottom line:\n- **For historical Teams context:** usable.\n- **For “what was said today” or very recent message certainty:** I would treat it as potentially stale.\n- **For anything decision-critical today:** don’t rely on Teams retrieval alone; cross-check with email, meetings, or direct live confirmation.\n\nWhat’s missing:\n- I don’t have a direct live freshness/status tool for Teams sync in the evidence I can see here, so I can’t prove current-day sync health beyond that known limitation.\n\nIf you want, I can still search Teams plus email plus meetings on a topic and tell you where the freshest signal actually is.",
